column12: 1. Make sure to check damselfish. Not sure if all damsel sp 1's are the same or if all damsel sp 2's are the same, etc. In other words, if you figure out what species one of the damselfish is and it's labled as damsel sp 1, don't automatically change all the damsel sp 1's to that species. I would check each damselfish. They were very hard to both identify and tell apart because they were often too dark.

2. Also, when starting a new box, always remember to check for repeated tiles from last box (I know that Jenn knows this, but this is good to know for the volunteer that does fish ID after I leave. I usually bring up both pictures of the tiles and compare to make sure that it's not the same tile and in the same location of the reef.

3. For any sp, if it is located in the yellowed out (repeated) data, then it should be disregarded completely. For example, if there is a fish sp 10 in the yellowed out area and a fish sp 10 in the non yellowed out area, this does not mean that these are necessarily the same fish. The yellowed out data should all be disgarded anyway, but just in case there is any confusion, I wanted to clarity. The yellowed out data is not just repeated, but also outdated. The data itself could be inaccurate.

4. Jenn, I will be sending you a word doc where I kept track of which tiles data was collected from in each box. This was mainly for me to use as I went through and yellowed out all the data that came from repeated tiles and so that I didn't repeat tiles in the future, but I wanted you to have it for your reference as well. I was also in the middle of hasluns box 3, so the volunteer that does this after me should be sure not to repeat those tiles. The ones I have already done for hasluns box 3 are written down in that word doc, but the volunteer can also reference this spreadsheet to make sure they don't repeat the tiles I already did for that box.
5. Thank you so much for the experience, Jenn! Not just with the fish ID, but all the diving as well. I had fun and learned a lot!
